The Department of Mathematics and Statistics at Texas Tech University has organized a Red Raider Mini-Symposium every year for the past 10 years. This symposium showcases particular areas of current mathematical importance through talks given by distinguished mathematicians and scientists and promising early-career researchers. In 2010, the 10th Red Raider Mini-Symposium entitled \textbf{Mathematical Modeling in Population Biology and Epidemiology} was held on October 28-30 at Texas Tech University in Lubbock, Texas.  The symposium featured 7 distinguished speakers, 4 early-career speakers, and 24 poster presentations by graduate students and young researchers.  The Mini-Symposium  is funded in part by Dr. Frits Ruymgaart, Paul Whitfield Horn Professor in the Department of Mathematics and Statistics at Texas Tech University and by the National Science Foundation.

Intellectual Merit.  The theme for the symposium is mathematical modeling in population biology and epidemiology. This interdisciplinary  area utilizes mathematical techniques and applies  them to current problems in population biology and epidemiology. The research areas of the speakers emphasize various mathematical approaches to several application areas. During the symposium, current research problems  and important open problems  were addressed. Additionally, the interactions among speakers and attendees lead to new opportunities for collaborations.   Lectures were presented by the 7 distinguished speakers:
C. Castillo-Chavez, Arizona State University;
J. Cushing, University of Arizona;
Z. Feng, Purdue University;
S.-B. Hsu, National Tsing-Hua University, Taiwan;
H. Thieme, University of Arizona;
G. F. Webb, Vanderbilt University; and
P. van den Driessche, University of Victoria, Canada.



Broader Impacts. The symposium  enhances the infrastructure for research as it establishes and strengthens a network of mathematicians, biologists, and public health professionals with shared interests in applications of mathematics to  population biology and epidemiology. % The event was a medium for interactions and discussions among senior scholars,  early career investigators, researchers, and students.
The symposium presented a high level of mathematical research; provided a stimulus to higher education; and promoted  interdisciplinary interaction among  mathematicians, public health professionals,  biologists, and other scientists in West Texas and the surrounding region. Participants  were from across the United States, Canada, and Taiwan.  The event engaged a diverse mixture of undergraduate and graduate students from the Texas Tech Department of Mathematics and Statistics as well as students from other departments in the university and from the Texas Tech Health Sciences Center in symposium-related activities. This symposium provided opportunities for young investigators to learn about  current problems in interdisciplinary research in population biology and epidemiology and to meet with the leaders in the field.

